[1]
Date: Wed 23 Jan 2008
Source: The New Indian Express [edited]
<http://www.newindpress.com/NewsItems.asp?ID=IEA20080123001527&Page=A&Title=Southern+News+-+Andhra+Pradesh&Topic=0>

Anthrax in Chittoor a sporadic phenomenon
-----------------------------------------
Despite the claim of the district administration on eradication of anthrax,
sporadic cases of the disease were reported in Chittoor in the last 5
years. A glance at the Anthrax Outbreak Report (OBR) from 2003 of the
Animal Husbandry Department revealed that 9 cases of anthrax were reported
in 2003, 15 in 2004, 7 in 2005, 10 in 2006, and 11 in 2007. Two cases were
reported in the district so far [in 2008].
However, there had been no human deaths due to the affliction of the
disease from cattle since 1997, according to officials.
It may be noted here that after the death of 3 people due to anthrax at
Cheemalpenta in Penumur mandal in 1997, the Animal Husbandry Department
launched an intensive vaccination programme covering all the animals in the
affected villages.
Talking to "this website's newspaper", joint director of Animal Husbandry
Somasekhar said as a preventive measure in the villages where anthrax cases
were reported, vaccination of animals was taken up. Accordingly, the
department is conducting the vaccination programme in the villages once in
8 months, he said.
Meanwhile, district collector SS Rawat held a meeting with mandal level
officials of the Animal Husbandry Department here on Tuesday [22 Jan 2008]
and discussed the course of action to be followed to prevent anthrax.
Reviewing the disease status mandal-wise, Rawat urged the officials to
ensure proper distribution of antibiotics to contain the disease and
promote awareness among people about preventive measures. He directed the
medical officers of veterinary hospitals to stock anthrax vaccine to meet
any eventuality. The doctors of Primary Health Centres [PHC] were asked to
send reports to the collectorate if anyone afflicted with the disease was
admitted to PHCs.
Somasekhar said teams of veterinarians visited Jandlapeta in Karvetinagaram
mandal following reports of an outbreak of anthrax. The laboratory tests
revealed that sheep in the village died due to some urinary track infection
and not of anthrax. However, as a precautionary measure, an intensive
anti-anthrax campaign was taken up in villages in Karvetinagaram and
surrounding mandals, he said.
--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Brent Barrett
