Date: Wed 23 Jan 2008
From: Angamuthu Kumar <akm_70@yahoo.com>akm_70@yahoo.com>

re: ProMED-mail Anthrax, human, ovine - India: (Andra Pradesh), susp
20080122.0266
--------------------------------------------------------------------
I just received your mail. In fact I was aware of the report of human cases
with cutaneous lesions admitted in CMC [Christian Medical College] Vellore
after getting initial therapy at the government hospital at Vellore. [This
is just inside Tamil Nadu and south of Chittoor, which is in Andra Pradesh.
- Mod.MHJ] I am not sure (probably culture negative) about the culture
report from those skin lesions. But the state (Tamil Nadu) health minister
came out in the newspaper and television saying that these cases were not
associated with anthrax and he as well said that enough measures are being
taken to vaccinate the cattle in the affected village by the animal
husbandry unit. But to my knowledge there were reports of death of sheep in
this village near Chittoor. These were handled by the local people,
following which cutaneous lesions were noticed in some contacts. If there
is any further information, I will relay it to you.
--
Dr Angamuthu Kumar
Clinical microbiologist & Infection control officer
<akm_70@yahoo.com>akm_70@yahoo.com>
[While the affected sheep in Jandlapeta village in Karvetinagaram mandal
appear to have died of some urinary problem, the official response is
either still suspicious of anthrax or is taking advantage of the event to
get caught up on their livestock vaccination. Claims of eradication by the
district authorities in the face of ongoing sporadic cases tells me that
the control and surveillance of this disease had fallen into abeyance. If
these villagers did suffer from some form of cutaneous lesion it would
definitely raise suspicions of something possibly indicative of cutaneous
anthrax. It is difficult to confirm human cutaneous cases largely because
of prior access to oral antibiotics and the sensitivity of _Bacillus
anthracis_ to antibiotics. Thus though the signs are all there, they will
be culture negative. But they could well be staphylococcal infections. So
at this point the decision is best described as "probably negative" until
we get any further information.
Thanks to Brent and Angamuthu for these updates. - Mod.MHJ]
